On Thanksgiving Day, President Donald Trump issued a proclamation expressing gratitude for the blessings in the lives of Americans. He emphasized the importance of faith, family, and friendship, and acknowledged the principles of freedom, liberty, and democracy that make the United States exceptional. The proclamation also highlighted the 400th anniversary of the Mayflower's journey to America, which brought the first seeds of democracy and the spirit of self-determination. Despite the challenges posed by the coronavirus pandemic, the proclamation praised the courage and generosity of the American people, particularly first responders, medical professionals, and essential workers. It also recognized the sacrifices made by the military, law enforcement, and first responders. The proclamation called on Americans to gather and offer prayers of thanks to God for their blessings. Finally, President Trump declared Thursday, November 26, 2020, as a National Day of Thanksgiving.